    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait so i think i got confused. i actually meant i wanted to find the relative major of a *minor* key. if i'm playing in c minor, how do i use the circle to find the major key that goes with it? and does the circle show how the keys cycle through each other?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you are in C minor, you find its relative major by moving up a relative major third, which brings you to E-flat Major. The circle of fifths shows how keys relate by moving by perfect fifths (or down by fourths); when you move clockwise, you are going up a fifth to the next key. This cyclical nature is what connects all the keys together, showing how they relate harmonically.",
      "source": "target",
